column269: I generally start with 40% on the fixed income. If the whole portfolio goes down  I will raise the percentage of A. If it goes up  I will do the opposite. When the total amount hit 10 or more  I will choose near 50% on each asset ( the exact amount is choosen quite randomly). Also  every time when the total amount hits 10  I will buy the lottery.
I made sure to invest at least $1 in asset B. When I earned more than 11.00 or so I would adjust and raise my investment for B accordingly.

I started out each period by placing 60% in Asset A and 40% in Asset B.  From there I tried to keep a base amount (using Asset B) pretty stable in order to ensure I had a decent amount of money at the end.
it was like real life investing. I'm a rish averse person so I tend to split the asset into 50/ 50. But the result is not as satisfying as risk taking

column263: International Relations/East Asian Languages and Cultures
column269: I did it largely randomly because I'm very bad at thinking strategically or with probability. I tried to keep Asset B steady  but sometimes I would randomly invest more in Asset A just to see if I would get lucky.

I was a bit disappointed that every time I paid a dollar for a chance to win twenty dollars  I never won. I usually bet the dollar when I had more than seven dollars. Whenever the last multiplier was high  I would invest less in A. Whenever the last multiplier was low  I would invest more in A. This was a pretty fun experiment.
